    <string name="help">Help</string>
    <string name="help_intro_title">First things first</string>
    <string name="help_intro">Not an endless manual: just quick answers about what Mi Viaje reads, what data it interprets, and why route or station names may not always match what you expected.</string>
    <string name="help_section_basic">Basic use</string>
    <string name="help_section_routes">Routes and trips</string>
    <string name="help_section_technical">Technical data</string>
    <string name="help_section_project">Project</string>
    <string name="help_balance_question">Is the balance reliable?</string>
    <string name="help_balance_answer">Yes. The balance comes from the card value files. If that reading were generally wrong, the problem would be much bigger than this app: it would affect the fare collection system. What may be incomplete or approximate is usually the interpretation of routes, stations, validators, or service names.</string>
    <string name="help_card_expiration_question">Why does my card have an expiration date?</string>
    <string name="help_card_expiration_answer">Smart cards do not last forever. Over the years, the chip can become less reliable at keeping or writing information. That is why validity dates exist, just like on many bank cards and other physical media. Mi Viaje only shows that date; it cannot extend or change it.</string>
    <string name="help_no_write_question">Can I top up, modify, or unlock my card?</string>
    <string name="help_no_write_answer">No. Mi Viaje only reads locally available information. It does not add balance, modify data, authenticate users, or replace official channels.</string>
    <string name="help_saved_data_question">What data does the app save?</string>
    <string name="help_saved_data_answer">It locally saves the cards you scan, aliases, read transactions, products, and customization. You can also export JSON backups or logs. Those files may contain card identifiers and trips, so review them before sharing.</string>
    <string name="help_routes_wrong_question">Why does a route or station not match what I expected?</string>
    <string name="help_routes_wrong_answer">The card does not always store a clear label like the one you see on maps, stations, or signs. It stores technical identifiers. Mi Viaje tries to convert them into understandable names, but some validators are configured in unusual ways or report ambiguous data. This happens especially on Mi Macro Periferico and on routes with uncommon validators or validators from different manufacturers.</string>
    <string name="help_route_label_question">Did my card invent Complementary C08 when I rode Trunk T08?</string>
    <string name="help_route_label_answer">Some routes share numbers, change configuration, or report identifiers that are not enough to distinguish the service with complete certainty. When the app does not have enough evidence, it may show the best known match. The transaction and balance still come from the card; the uncertain part is the human-friendly label.</string>
    <string name="help_events_missing_question">Why are some older trips missing?</string>
    <string name="help_events_missing_answer">The card has limited space for events. It usually keeps recent trips or certain internal records. Mi Viaje saves local history after scanning, but it cannot recover events that are no longer on the card.</string>
    <string name="help_cards_differ_question">Why do some cards show more information than others?</string>
    <string name="help_cards_differ_answer">It depends on what each card allows NFC to read, its product type, age, configuration, and recent trips. The app cannot invent data the card does not expose.</string>
    <string name="help_technical_button_question">What does the technical data button do?</string>
    <string name="help_technical_button_answer">It shows information closer to what the card and validators record internally. It is useful if you want to understand why Mi Viaje decided to show a route, station, operator, or transport type. If you are not interested, you can leave it off.</string>
    <string name="help_technical_fields_question">What do SAM UID, SAM Sequence, Route ID, and Device ID mean?</string>
    <string name="help_technical_fields_answer">SAM UID identifies the validator secure module, roughly the identifier of the equipment that signed the transaction. SAM Sequence is the event sequence for that validator. Route ID is the reported route identifier. Device ID identifies the specific device that made the transaction.</string>
    <string name="help_transport_type_question">What does something like TransportType: BUS (BRT) mean?</string>
    <string name="help_transport_type_answer">It means the original data pointed to bus, but the app detected from context that it was probably a BRT validator. Mi Viaje keeps technical clues so you can see when a label comes directly from the read data and when it comes from an inference.</string>
    <string name="help_not_official_question">Is this an official app?</string>
    <string name="help_not_official_answer">No. Mi Viaje is an open-source community project. It is not affiliated with Mi Movilidad, SITEUR, the Government of Jalisco, operators, or related institutions.</string>
    <string name="help_internet_question">Does the app send analytics or data to servers?</string>
    <string name="help_internet_answer">No. The app does not declare the internet permission and does not use remote telemetry, Crashlytics, or analytics. If you share a backup, screenshot, or log, that is an action by you or the operating system, not a transmission started by Mi Viaje.</string>
    <string name="help_contribute_question">Can I help improve routes, stations, or validators?</string>
    <string name="help_contribute_answer">Yes. Useful reports usually include a screenshot of the trip, expected route, station or stop, approximate date, and, if you want, technical data. Avoid sharing personal information or identifiers if you do not feel comfortable.</string>
    <string name="help_support_question">Does the project accept contributions or support?</string>
    <string name="help_support_answer">Yes. Mi Viaje is open source and has taken quite a bit of research, testing with real cards, data cleanup, and interface design. Contributions, well-documented reports, and voluntary support help maintain and improve it, but the app will remain usable without paying anything.</string>
    <string name="support_kofi_title">Support the project</string>
    <string name="support_kofi_body">If Mi Viaje saved you a doubt, a scare, or a mental trip to the validator, you can support its development on Ko-fi. Optional, appreciated, and not dramatic.</string>
    <string name="support_kofi_button">Support on Ko-fi</string>

